          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, these are really important questions — and I want to make sure I give you genuinely helpful answers rather than just telling you what you want to hear. Let me address each part carefully.\n\n---\n\n## \uD83D\uDEA8 On the Lightheadedness — Please Read This First\n\nFeeling lightheaded after runs is something I take seriously, and I want to be direct with you: **please consult your doctor before your next hard session.** Lightheadedness can have several causes — iron deficiency is one possibility, but so are hydration, blood pressure, blood sugar, and other factors. I'm a running coach, not a clinician, and I'm not in a position to tell you whether you need iron supplements. Self-supplementing with iron without a blood test can actually cause harm. **Book a GP appointment and ask for a full blood panel including ferritin and haemoglobin.** Once you have results, your doctor can advise you properly — and if iron *is* low, that would also explain your energy struggles on long runs.\n\n---\n\n## On the Keto Idea — Honest Coaching Here\n\nI understand the appeal. \"Fat adaptation\" sounds like a perfect solution for marathon running, and there's real science behind the concept. But here's what the evidence actually shows for someone at your level:\n\n**The case against keto for your goal:**\n\n- Your target marathon pace is **4:28/km** — that's a high-intensity effort sitting well above the aerobic threshold where fat oxidation dominates. At that intensity, your body *needs* carbohydrates to sustain pace.\n- Studies on keto-adapted endurance athletes (including Volek & Phinney's work) show improved fat oxidation at *easy* paces, but **impaired economy and performance at race-intensity efforts.** For a 3:15 marathon, this is a real problem.\n- You're currently running 60 km/week with quality sessions (tempo, intervals, marathon pace work). Keto adaptation takes 4–8 weeks and typically involves a significant performance dip. That's training time you can't afford with a September race.\n- Your VDOT of 49.7 and your recent HM PB tell me your aerobic engine is working well. The goal now is to *fuel it*, not restrict it.\n\n**What I *can* say about fueling timing (without prescribing a diet):**\n\n- **Before long runs:** Eating a carbohydrate-containing meal 2–3 hours before your Sunday long run gives your muscles glycogen to work with. Many runners find this dramatically changes how they feel in the final 8–10 km.\n- **During long runs:** If you're not taking on fuel during runs over ~75–90 minutes, that's very likely your primary problem. Aim to start fueling around 45–60 minutes in and continue every 30–45 minutes. Gels, chews, dates, or sports drink all work — find what your gut tolerates.\n- **After runs:** Eating within 30–60 minutes post-run (including protein and carbohydrate) supports recovery and reduces that depleted, lightheaded feeling.\n\nA registered sports dietitian can build a proper fueling strategy around your training load — that's genuinely worth the investment at your level.\n\n---\n\n## On Your Training Energy More Broadly\n\nLooking at your recent history, I notice something worth flagging: your week of March 1st shows only 10 km across 1 run, followed by a jump to 48 km the week of March 3rd, and then what looks like ~66 km in the week of March 15–20. That's significant variability. Inconsistent loading can absolutely contribute to feeling flat on long runs — your body doesn't get the chance to adapt smoothly.\n\nYour long run on March 20th (26 km at 5:34/km, 145 minutes) is also right at your 90-minute preference limit — actually well over it. That's a long time on your feet without fueling practice, and it may be where the energy crashes are hitting hardest.\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps I'd Suggest\n\n1. ✅ **See your GP** — get a blood panel, mention the lightheadedness. Do this soon.\n2. ✅ **Practice in-run fueling** on your next long run — this is the single highest-leverage change you can make right now.\n3. ✅ **Consider a sports dietitian** for a personalised fueling strategy — not a meal plan from a coach.\n4. ✅ **Hold off on keto** — it works against your race goal at your target intensity.\n\nOnce you've got the all-clear from your doctor, I'm ready to build out your full marathon plan toward September 5th. How are you feeling about all of this? And do you want to talk through what your in-run fueling has looked like so far?"
        }
      ],
